President Donald J. Trump has issued a proclamation declaring September 2019 as National Childhood Cancer Awareness Month. The proclamation recognizes the brave young Americans who are fighting cancer and remembers those who have lost their lives to the disease. It also reaffirms the nation's commitment to developing cures for pediatric cancer and improving the quality of life for childhood cancer survivors. The proclamation highlights the progress made in increasing the life expectancy of children and adolescents with cancer and mentions the Childhood Cancer Survivorship, Treatment, Access, and Research (STAR) Act, which supports research and treatment for childhood cancers. The President also expresses his commitment to investing $500 million over the next decade in cancer-related research. The proclamation encourages all Americans to observe the month with programs and activities that raise awareness of efforts to find a cure for childhood cancer.